  "prompt": "How does magnesium oxide react with water?",
  "response": "Magnesium oxide (MgO) reacts with water to form magnesium hydroxide (Mg(OH)2). Here's the chemical equation for this reaction:\n\nMgO + H2O \u2192 Mg(OH)2\n\nThis reaction is classified as a base hydrolysis reaction. When magnesium oxide is added to water, it dissolves and reacts to produce magnesium hydroxide, which is a base. The reaction is relatively slow and not highly exothermic. Magnesium hydroxide has limited solubility in water and appears as a white precipitate. This compound is commonly known as milk of magnesia and is used in antacids and laxatives.\n\nKey characteristics of the reaction:\n- Produces magnesium hydroxide\n- Is a base-forming reaction\n- Relatively mild reaction\n- Limited solubility of the product",
